ters between occupiers and occupied was closely linked to the disintegration of the Japanese empire and the rise of U.S. hegemony in the Asia-Pacific region during the Cold War era. Shedding new light on the configuration of postwar Japan, the process of decolonization, the postcolonial formation of the Asia-Pacific region, and the particularities of postwar U.S. imperialism, Sanitized Sex offers a reading of the intimacies of empires—defeated and victorious.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2023) 0aProstitutesxLegal status, laws, etczJapanxHistoryy20th century. 0aProstitutesxLegal status, laws, etc.zJapanxHistoryy20th century. 0aSex-oriented businesseszJapanxHistoryy20th century. 0aSexually transmitted diseaseszJapanxPreventionxHistoryy20th century. 0aSoldiersxSexual behaviorzJapan. 0aSoldiersxSexual behaviorzUnited States. 7aHISTORY / Asia / General.2bisacsh  aamerica.  aasia pacific region.  aclass.  acold war.  acultural history.  adecolonization.  agender.  aintimacy.  ajapan.  ajapanese empire.  aoccupation of japan.  apost war empire building.  apostwar japan.  aprostitution.  arace.  aregulations.  asecond world war.  aself imagery.  asex work.  asexual encounters.  asexuality.  asocial history.  aunited states imperialism.  aus japanese relations.  avenereal disease.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Contemporary Collection eBook Packagez978311064982608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z97831106675540 cprintz978052029597140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780520968691?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520968691423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520968691/original  a978-3-11-064982-6  Asia